# Docker Ops

The image (`vane-glm`) bundles Next.js + SearxNG. State (config, sqlite,
uploads) lives in the `vane-data` volume at `/home/vane/data`.

## Build is slow

The `exporting layers` step takes ~10-30 min on Docker Desktop. Always
background the build and notify on completion; don't block on it.

```bash
docker build -t vane-glm .
```

## Swap pattern

Always stop + remove before re-run, and keep the volume name stable so
config persists:

```bash
docker stop vane && docker rm vane
docker run -d -p 4567:3000 -v vane-data:/home/vane/data --name vane vane-glm
```

If you change the port, only change the left side (`4567:3000`) — the
container listens on 3000 internally.

## config.json lives in the volume, not source

Provider API keys (z.ai, Gemini) and model selections are in
`/home/vane/data/config.json` inside the volume. Source code never
contains keys. To edit:

```bash
docker stop vane
docker cp vane:/home/vane/data/config.json /tmp/vane-config.json
# edit /tmp/vane-config.json; recompute any changed provider's hash
docker cp /tmp/vane-config.json vane:/home/vane/data/config.json
docker start vane
```

A `docker rm` + `docker run` (with the same `-v vane-data` volume)
preserves config across recreations. Only `docker volume rm vane-data`
loses it.

## Verify after every swap

```bash
docker ps --filter name=vane
docker logs --tail 30 vane
```

Then hard-refresh the browser (Cmd+Shift+R) — cached JS masks new builds.
Run a speed-mode query to confirm the pipeline before declaring done.

## Entrypoint

`entrypoint.sh` starts SearxNG then Vane. SearxNG init takes ~10-20s; the
app isn't ready until you see `Ready on http://0.0.0.0:3000` in the logs.
